            A kidney transplant is permanent; the patient does not need to maintain access to a hospital.
    c?
        When the immune system detects a foreign body, lymphocytes produce antibodies, which bind to the foreign body. The foreign body is then swallowed by phagocytes using pseudopodia, and taken into the phagocytes' vacuole, where enzymes are secreted to break it down.

        There is also fever to try to kill the disease, inflammation to protect the afflicted area(s), coughing and sneezing to try to expel the pathogen.
    d?
        The chances of rejection are lower if the kidney comes from a close relative because the kidney would be more genetically similar to the receiver. This would mean that the body is less likely to identify it as a foreign body and attack it, so the chances of rejection are lower.
