    a? [Density of water]
        Since we know the difference in temperature (final - initial temperature), and we know water's specific heat capacity (4.2 joules per gram-degree celcius), and we know the mass of the water since we know the density of water and we can multiply the volume of water (20 cm^3) by the density of water, and the water absorbs the (heat) energy released by 1g of the grain, we can calculate the increase in energy in the water using the formula energy = 4.2 * mass of water * (end temperature - starting temperature); and the formula mass of water = density of water (in g/cm^3) * volume of water (20 cm^3).
    b.
        The scientists can repeat the experiment with fresh water and grain three times per grain-type.
    c.
        i.
            A twisted waste gas pipe increases the amount of time the hot gas leaving the grain can transfer energy to the water as the gas must travel for longer while transferring energy. If there is significant energy left in the hot gas as it leaves the apparatus, then that is energy which is not measured, reducing accuracy. Hence, this increases accuracy.
        ii.
            So complete combustion occurs as there is more oxygen as opposed to incomplete combustion which happens when there is not enough oxygen, which releases less energy.
    d.
        i.
            7 * .65 = 4.55g
        ii.
            Rice has the most carbohydrate, but the least protein. Oats have a high amount (but not the highest) of fat, protein, and carbohydrate. Rye has the least fat, but also a low amount of protein. However, they have a relatively high amount of carbohydrate compared to wheat.

            Wheat has the highest amount of protein, but also the highest amount of fat, and the lowest amount of carbohydrate.

            Energy-wise, oats > rice > wheat > rye. Fibre-wise, rye = wheat > oats > rice.

            A long-distance athlete likely needs an energy-dense food, but, being an athlete, would also need high protein. The athlete would likely not want to consume foods with a high amount of fat. If that is not an issue, however, wheat would be a good choice, as it has the highest amount of protein. If it is an issue, oats is likely the best choice, as it is the most energy dense and also has a respectable amount of protein.

            However, the long-distance athlete might already get enough protein from another source. In that case, rye would be a good choice, as it has a high amount of fibre and a low amount of fat.

            Right before race-day, the athlete might choose to consume rice as rice has the most carbohydrates, to provide energy in delayed-release form.
3.
    a?
        Stem cells are different from most body cells because they are not specialised, and can differentiate into (in the case of embryonic stem cells) any other specialised cell, or (in the case of adult stem cells) into red blood cells via erythropoiesis.
    b? [How does the fibrin/fibrinogen come in?]
        When there is damage in a blood-vessel in the body, a blood clot is formed to prevent severe blood loss, which would be fatal. Platelets are vital in the formation of blood clots as they trap red blood cells to form the blood clot.
    c?
        Vaccination is the introduction of weakened viruses or bacteria, or fragments thereof, causing antibodies to be produced. These antibodies, being soluble proteins, stay in the plasma until the body is infected for real, at which point they are able to react quicker than if vaccination had not occurred, which helps prevent the disease from reproducing or reproducing as quickly, hence protecting the body from disease.
    d?
        Blood stem cells can be used to treat a variety of blood disorders because a transplanted blood stem cell will then reproduce to make more blood stem cells, and also differentiate into well-formed red and white blood cells.
