            If a person moves to a hot environment, vasodilation occurs. Sphincters surrounding the blood vessels in the skin relax, allowing blood to flow closer to the surface of the skin so heat can be transferred.
    b.
        i.
            Sweating rate in litres per hour.
        ii.
            draw dotted lines;
            1.7 litres/hour * 15/60 = 0.425 litres
        iii.
            As running speed increases, the sweating rate increases. This is likely because there is waste heat generated as muscles contract to make the person run, increasing body temperature, so sweating occurs to cool the person down. As the person runs faster, more heat is generated, so more sweating occurs.

            There is more sweating at all speeds in the hot and humid environment. This is likely because the environment being hot means the person's body temperature was already high, and being humid means sweat is less effective at cooling the person down. Moreover, the rate of increase in volume of sweat is lower for the cool and dry environment at first, indicating that the increased gradient in temperature had increased cooling somewhat and hence that not as much of an increase in sweat was necessary.
